1
00:00:00,710 --> 00:00:05,560
As a trader, you are probably familiar with
several theories concerning market structure

2
00:00:05,560 --> 00:00:06,910
and cycles.

3
00:00:06,910 --> 00:00:11,559
Some of the more popular ones include the
Elliott Wave Principle and the Dow Theory.

4
00:00:11,559 --> 00:00:16,230
In today’s video, I plan to add one more
important type of market analysis to your

5
00:00:16,230 --> 00:00:22,419
trading arsenal, namely a price action based
approach known as the Wyckoff trading method.

6
00:00:22,419 --> 00:00:27,449
The Wyckoff Method consists of a series of
principles and strategies which can be applied

7
00:00:27,449 --> 00:00:29,390
to all sorts of financial markets.

8
00:00:29,390 --> 00:00:33,989
I will break Wyckoff’s method into 4 parts:
• The three laws of Wyckoff

9
00:00:33,989 --> 00:00:36,839
• The Composite Man
• Wyckoff Price Cycle

10
00:00:36,839 --> 00:00:39,430
• Wyckoff Volume Spread Analysis

11
00:00:39,430 --> 00:00:41,390
The three laws of Wyckoff

12
00:00:41,390 --> 00:00:43,880
Wyckoff's method rests on three fundamental
“laws”.

13
00:00:43,880 --> 00:00:44,880
1.

14
00:00:44,880 --> 00:00:48,750
The law of supply and demand
When demand is greater than supply, prices

15
00:00:48,750 --> 00:00:52,940
rise, and when supply is greater than demand,
prices fall.

16
00:00:52,940 --> 00:00:57,739
The trader can study the balance between supply
and demand by comparing price and volume bars

17
00:00:57,739 --> 00:01:01,980
over time, as a way to better visualize the
relation between supply and demand.

18
00:01:01,980 --> 00:01:06,590
This often provides insights into the next
market movements.

19
00:01:06,590 --> 00:01:07,750
2.

20
00:01:07,750 --> 00:01:11,580
The Law of Cause and Effect
The second law states that the differences

21
00:01:11,580 --> 00:01:13,640
between supply and demand are not random.

22
00:01:13,640 --> 00:01:18,610
Instead, they come after periods of preparation,
as a result of specific events.

23
00:01:18,610 --> 00:01:25,610
In Wyckoff's terms, a period of accumulation
(cause) eventually leads to an uptrend (effect).

24
00:01:25,610 --> 00:01:31,369
In contrast, a period of distribution (cause)
eventually results in a downtrend (effect).

25
00:01:31,369 --> 00:01:32,450
3.

26
00:01:32,450 --> 00:01:38,520
The Law of Effort vs. Result
The third Wyckoff law states that the changes

27
00:01:38,520 --> 00:01:43,500
in an asset’s price are a result of an effort,
which is represented by the trading volume.

28
00:01:43,500 --> 00:01:47,840
If the price action is in harmony with the
volume, there is a good chance the trend will

29
00:01:47,840 --> 00:01:48,840
continue.

30
00:01:48,840 --> 00:01:53,140
But, if the volume and price diverge, the
market trend is likely to stop or change direction.

31
00:01:53,140 --> 00:01:58,469
For instance, imagine that a market starts
to consolidate with a very high volume after

32
00:01:58,469 --> 00:02:00,420
a long bearish trend.

33
00:02:00,420 --> 00:02:04,250
The high volume indicates a big effort, but
the sideways movement suggests a small result.

34
00:02:04,250 --> 00:02:09,190
So, there is a lot of activity, but no more
significant price drops.

35
00:02:09,190 --> 00:02:14,000
Such a situation could indicate that the downtrend
may be over, and a reversal is near.

36
00:02:14,000 --> 00:02:17,420
The Composite Man
Wyckoff created the idea of the Composite

37
00:02:17,420 --> 00:02:20,690
Man as an imaginary identity of the market.

38
00:02:20,690 --> 00:02:25,390
He proposed that investors and traders should
study the stock market as if a single entity

39
00:02:25,390 --> 00:02:26,390
was controlling it.

40
00:02:26,390 --> 00:02:32,210
It always acts in his own best interest to
ensure he can buy low and sell high.

41
00:02:32,210 --> 00:02:36,780
Think of composite man as an evil entity,
like the bad guy in a movie, sitting behind

42
00:02:36,780 --> 00:02:40,160
the scenes controlling markets by pushing
buttons.

43
00:02:40,160 --> 00:02:43,650
His goal is to move the markets to your disadvantage.

44
00:02:43,650 --> 00:02:50,230
The composite man is continually seeking to
maximize his profit at “your” expense.

45
00:02:50,230 --> 00:02:55,260
The Composite Man’s behavior is the opposite
of retail traders, but according to Wyckoff,

46
00:02:55,260 --> 00:03:00,730
the Composite Man uses a somewhat predictable
strategy, from which traders can learn from.

47
00:03:00,730 --> 00:03:06,310
Here are some main ideas of composite man:
• Composite man plans and executes his deception

48
00:03:06,310 --> 00:03:09,820
well in advance
• Composite man is there to fool you to

49
00:03:09,820 --> 00:03:15,020
buying positions that he has already accumulated
• Composite man will tempt you to sell at

50
00:03:15,020 --> 00:03:18,710
the worst possible time
• Composite man leaves subtle evidence of

51
00:03:18,710 --> 00:03:21,090
his strategy for those who understand him

52
00:03:21,090 --> 00:03:26,310
Now, let’s use the Composite Man concept
to illustrate a market cycle.

53
00:03:26,310 --> 00:03:27,310
1.

54
00:03:27,310 --> 00:03:29,210
Accumulation
The process of accumulation is the first stage

55
00:03:29,210 --> 00:03:31,450
of the Wyckoff price cycle.

56
00:03:31,450 --> 00:03:35,010
The Composite Man accumulates assets before
most investors.

57
00:03:35,010 --> 00:03:39,670
The accumulation is done gradually to avoid
the price from changing significantly.

58
00:03:39,670 --> 00:03:46,050
Bulls are gaining power slowly and as a result,
they are poised to push prices higher.

59
00:03:46,050 --> 00:03:50,511
Although the Accumulation stage is related
with the bulls gaining authority, the price

60
00:03:50,511 --> 00:03:52,800
action on the chart is flat.

61
00:03:52,800 --> 00:03:57,450
In other words, the process of accumulation
is illustrated by a ranging price structure

62
00:03:57,450 --> 00:03:59,010
on the chart.

63
00:03:59,010 --> 00:04:03,810
Higher lows within the range is usually considered
a signal that the price action is currently

64
00:04:03,810 --> 00:04:05,020
in an Accumulation phase.

65
00:04:05,020 --> 00:04:06,020
2.

66
00:04:06,020 --> 00:04:08,940
Markup Phase (Uptrend)
The Markup is the second stage of the Wyckoff

67
00:04:08,940 --> 00:04:10,450
trading cycle.

68
00:04:10,450 --> 00:04:14,810
When the Composite Man is holding enough power,
and the selling force is depleted, he starts

69
00:04:14,810 --> 00:04:16,350
pushing the market up.

70
00:04:16,350 --> 00:04:20,509
The emerging trend attracts more investors,
causing demand to increase.

71
00:04:20,509 --> 00:04:23,759
There may be multiple phases of accumulation
during an uptrend.

72
00:04:23,759 --> 00:04:29,180
We may call them re-accumulation phases, where
the bigger trend stops and consolidates for

73
00:04:29,180 --> 00:04:32,219
a while, before continuing its upward movement.

74
00:04:32,219 --> 00:04:35,629
As the market moves up, other traders are
encouraged to buy.

75
00:04:35,629 --> 00:04:39,379
At this point, demand is higher than supply.

76
00:04:39,379 --> 00:04:40,699
3.

77
00:04:40,699 --> 00:04:42,180
Distribution
The Distribution process is the third stage

78
00:04:42,180 --> 00:04:44,000
of the Wyckoff price cycle.

79
00:04:44,000 --> 00:04:47,900
Here, the Composite Man starts distributing
his holdings.

80
00:04:47,900 --> 00:04:52,810
He sells his profitable positions to those
entering the market at a late stage.

81
00:04:52,810 --> 00:04:58,229
The distribution phase is marked by a sideways
movement that absorbs demand until it gets

82
00:04:58,229 --> 00:04:59,229
exhausted.

83
00:04:59,229 --> 00:05:02,199
The price action on the chart at this stage
is flat.

84
00:05:02,199 --> 00:05:07,040
One indication that the market is in a Distribution
stage will be the sustained failure of price

85
00:05:07,040 --> 00:05:09,449
to create higher lows on the chart.

86
00:05:09,449 --> 00:05:13,810
The price action creates lower highs which
is an indication that the market is currently

87
00:05:13,810 --> 00:05:15,259
experiencing a selloff.

88
00:05:15,259 --> 00:05:16,259
4.

89
00:05:16,259 --> 00:05:19,100
Markdown Phase (Downtrend)
The Markdown is the last stage of the Wyckoff

90
00:05:19,100 --> 00:05:20,100
price cycle.

91
00:05:20,100 --> 00:05:25,090
Soon after the distribution phase, the market
starts reverting to the downside.

92
00:05:25,090 --> 00:05:28,020
After the Composite Man is done selling a
good amount of his shares, he starts pushing

93
00:05:28,020 --> 00:05:29,020
the market down.

94
00:05:29,020 --> 00:05:33,729
The supply becomes much greater than demand,
and the downtrend is established.

95
00:05:33,729 --> 00:05:38,189
When the bearish trend is finally over, a
new accumulation phase begins.

96
00:05:38,189 --> 00:05:41,469
Wyckoff Volume Spread Analysis
Volume is of a great importance for the Wyckoff

97
00:05:41,469 --> 00:05:46,289
trader, because it can provide valuable information
into what is really going on “behind the

98
00:05:46,289 --> 00:05:47,499
scenes”.

99
00:05:47,499 --> 00:05:52,271
Wyckoff Volume Analysis provides confirmation
of progressing events during the Wyckoff Price

100
00:05:52,271 --> 00:05:53,509
Cycle.

101
00:05:53,509 --> 00:05:58,310
As I said earlier, high volumes can lead to
sustained price moves on the chart.

102
00:05:58,310 --> 00:06:03,689
Wyckoff Volume Spread Analysis also helps
you identify periods when the price is transitioning

103
00:06:03,689 --> 00:06:07,349
between the different stages of the Wyckoff
Price Cycle.

104
00:06:07,349 --> 00:06:11,650
When the price moves through a key level during
the Wyckoff Price Cycle, you should consider

105
00:06:11,650 --> 00:06:15,860
the move valid if the trading volumes are
relatively high during the breakout.

106
00:06:15,860 --> 00:06:20,949
If the volumes are decreasing, then you are
probably looking at a spring (which is a false

107
00:06:20,949 --> 00:06:24,610
breakout) rather than a real breakout.

108
00:06:24,610 --> 00:06:26,499
This is an example of an Accumulation stage.

109
00:06:26,499 --> 00:06:30,879
Notice on the chart that the first two bottoms
are slightly increasing.

110
00:06:30,879 --> 00:06:34,159
This hints that the market is likely in an
accumulating stage.

111
00:06:34,159 --> 00:06:37,919
Suddenly, we see a bearish breakdown through
the lower level of the range.

112
00:06:37,919 --> 00:06:42,520
However, the volume is decreasing during the
breakdown through the level, which suggests

113
00:06:42,520 --> 00:06:48,259
that this could be a false breakout (Spring)
before the real breakout actually takes place.

114
00:06:48,259 --> 00:06:53,469
The price reverses after the breakdown and
at the same time, the trading volume is increasing.

115
00:06:53,469 --> 00:06:57,399
This is a strong indication that the Price
Cycle is likely entering the second stage

116
00:06:57,399 --> 00:06:58,990
– the Markup.

117
00:06:58,990 --> 00:07:04,529
How to apply Wyckoff method in your trading
Traders can use the Wyckoff Price Cycle to

118
00:07:04,529 --> 00:07:06,780
recognize upcoming price moves.

119
00:07:06,780 --> 00:07:11,400
For example, the end of an Accumulation stage
is the beginning of a Markup, which could

120
00:07:11,400 --> 00:07:13,439
be traded to the long side.

121
00:07:13,439 --> 00:07:17,889
At the same time, the end of a Distribution
stage is the beginning of a Markdown, which

122
00:07:17,889 --> 00:07:20,580
could be traded to the short side.

123
00:07:20,580 --> 00:07:24,559
Understanding the different stages within
the price cycle will allow you to position

124
00:07:24,559 --> 00:07:27,680
for the next most likely price tendency.

125
00:07:27,680 --> 00:07:32,860
Ideally, you should enter a trade when the
price action is transiting from Accumulation

126
00:07:32,860 --> 00:07:35,800
to Markup and from Distribution to Markdown.

127
00:07:35,800 --> 00:07:40,279
First, you would need to confirm the current
stage when the price is ranging.

128
00:07:40,279 --> 00:07:45,759
It would help to identify increasing bottoms
for an Accumulation and decreasing tops for

129
00:07:45,759 --> 00:07:46,759
Distribution.

130
00:07:46,759 --> 00:07:52,770
In addition, it would be useful to analyze
the previous price moves for additional clues.

131
00:07:52,770 --> 00:07:57,749
Another way you can attempt to confirm an
Accumulation or Distribution stage is by identifying

132
00:07:57,749 --> 00:08:02,129
a Spring, which is the transitional price
action behavior that often occurs between

133
00:08:02,129 --> 00:08:04,139
the cycle stages.

134
00:08:04,139 --> 00:08:09,240
Chart patterns can also be helpful in identifying
Accumulation and Distribution processes on

135
00:08:09,240 --> 00:08:10,419
the chart.

136
00:08:10,419 --> 00:08:14,710
The potential price move out of a pattern
could help you identify the transition to

137
00:08:14,710 --> 00:08:17,719
a Markup or a Markdown.

138
00:08:17,719 --> 00:08:22,259
The actual trade comes when the price action
breaks the range in the direction of the expected

139
00:08:22,259 --> 00:08:23,259
move.

140
00:08:23,259 --> 00:08:27,599
For example, you could buy when the price
breaks the flat range through the upper level.

141
00:08:27,599 --> 00:08:32,190
Contrary, you could sell when the price action
breaks the lower support level of the Distribution

142
00:08:32,190 --> 00:08:33,190
area.

143
00:08:33,190 --> 00:08:37,030
And, you must keep an eye on volume to confirm
that your decision is correct.

144
00:08:37,030 --> 00:08:41,150
If you are trading a Markup, your stop loss
should be located below the lowest point of

145
00:08:41,150 --> 00:08:43,130
the Accumulation stage.

146
00:08:43,130 --> 00:08:47,310
If you are trading a Markdown, then your stop
loss order should be positioned above the

147
00:08:47,310 --> 00:08:49,410
highest point during the Distribution stage.

148
00:08:49,410 --> 00:08:53,130
Here, the cycle begins with the Distribution
phase.

149
00:08:53,130 --> 00:08:57,180
At this point, the price action breaks the
upper level of the range.

150
00:08:57,180 --> 00:09:01,970
However, the trading volumes at that time
are decreasing, Therefore, we can reason that

151
00:09:01,970 --> 00:09:04,660
a Spring pattern on the chart may be forming.

152
00:09:04,660 --> 00:09:10,000
The price action reverses afterwards and breaks
the lower level of the Distribution channel

153
00:09:10,000 --> 00:09:11,600
on increasing volume.

154
00:09:11,600 --> 00:09:16,040
This was the ideal moment to enter a short
position, placing a stop loss above the highest

155
00:09:16,040 --> 00:09:17,990
point of the Distribution range.

156
00:09:17,990 --> 00:09:23,830
See that the Markdown begins right after the
selloff and the price of decreased aggressively.

157
00:09:23,830 --> 00:09:28,210
Then we see a sideways movement, which hints
that the Markdown phase is probably completed.

158
00:09:28,210 --> 00:09:32,350
If you haven’t reached your profit target,
you would close your trade when the price

159
00:09:32,350 --> 00:09:36,580
action begins to create increasing tops on
the chart.

160
00:09:36,580 --> 00:09:40,990
When price finishes a Markdown stage, it starts
an Accumulation.

161
00:09:40,990 --> 00:09:45,330
During the Accumulation, we see that the price
drops on decreasing volumes and breaks the

162
00:09:45,330 --> 00:09:48,840
channel downwards
Here, we see a breakout through the upper

163
00:09:48,840 --> 00:09:51,120
level of the Accumulation channel.

164
00:09:51,120 --> 00:09:54,530
This is a strong buy signal, which you could
use to go long.

165
00:09:54,530 --> 00:09:58,560
The stop loss order goes below the lowest
point of the Accumulation phase.

166
00:09:58,560 --> 00:10:05,000
The price action enters a Markup stage afterwards,
as the price rises creating higher highs.

167
00:10:05,000 --> 00:10:10,200
After a strong increase the price action starts
to range, suggesting the Markup stage is probably

168
00:10:10,200 --> 00:12:14,100
completed and the new Distribution stage is
on its way.

169
00:12:14,100 --> 00:12:18,330
This video was basically an introduction to
Wyckoff trading and I tried to keep things

170
00:12:18,330 --> 00:12:20,210
as simple as possible.

171
00:12:20,210 --> 00:12:24,770
If you enjoyed this type of content and want
more Wyckoff strategies, leave us a like to

172
00:12:24,770 --> 00:12:29,860
show your support and in future videos we’ll
go deeper with some advanced Wyckoff concepts

173
00:12:29,860 --> 00:12:34,490
that can be applied to day trading and swing
trading.

174
00:12:34,490 --> 00:12:34,830
Until next time.

